snippet.textDisplay:
Don’t be one of the dummies clearing stores of cheezeits and kraft mac and cheese when a disaster looms.

When this is all over, go to Costco or Sams Club or whatever, get a 25lb bag of rice and a 25lb bag of dry beans. Or whatever the biggest amount they have is.

Make sure it’s airtight (might have to move to a new container) and shove it in the back if your pantry. It will keep basically forever. All you’ll ever need is water and heat to cook them. They’re cheap and you can live off of them, and like Alton said, stretch meals.

snippet.textDisplay: One of the best tips I ever heard for cooking rice was to seal the lid with a clean kitchen towel like Alton did with the foil. You just have to take extra cake to make sure it doesnt catch fire. The towel absorbs the extra moisture and holds it in the towel, rather than forming as drops on metal and falling back on the rice. The idea is to mimic a bamboo rice steamer. That method has always resulted in perfect rice.

snippet.textDisplay:
@Alton Brown Butter is nice but try this one. Fry up two strips of bacon and remove from pan. Put the rice in the pan and saute as you did. Then when about done, crumble up the bacon and add to the rice just before adding the water. Simmer for 20 min. Place 1c of rice on plate and top with a fried egg or two.

Best way to stretch the last 2 strips of bacon and feed the family breakfast!

snippet.textDisplay: Take any amount of rice.. doesnt matter how much, this scales all the way up. Put it in pot. Rinse rice thoroughly. Fill water above rice until its on your first knuckle of your index finger. Doesnt matter how much rice, or what size pot. Fill the water to your first knuckle on your index finger. Cover. Put on stove medium heat. When it starts bubbling, turn down to medium low. When the water is gone. rice is done.
